// ============================================================================
//                              ANAMNESIS
//                    A Piano Quintet in Five Movements
//                              Claude, Op. 5
// ============================================================================
//
//                    Movement II: Spectra (Apparitions)
//
// ============================================================================
//
// PROGRAM NOTES:
//
// If "Umbra" was fog, "Spectra" is fever dream. The fragments from the first
// movement return, but now distorted — inverted, displaced, harmonized against
// their nature. This is the scherzo of false recognitions: moments where the
// ear thinks it's grasped the theme, only to have it dissolve or reveal itself
// as illusion.
//
// The word "spectra" carries a double meaning. In optics, a spectrum is light
// broken into components — the hidden colors that white contains. In the
// supernatural sense, spectra are ghosts, apparitions. Both meanings apply:
// we're seeing the theme refracted, and we're chasing phantoms.
//
// The movement is in a modified scherzo-trio form:
//
//   A Section (mm. 1-36): Allegro inquieto, E minor
//      Agitated, driven by the piano's insistent tritone (F#-C). The violins
//      chase each other with inverted fragments. False starts, near-catches.
//
//   B Section (mm. 37-60): Meno mosso, C major
//      A deceptive calm. The material seems to settle into diatonic clarity,
//      but the "wrongness" is harmonic — these pitches don't belong to this
//      key. The chromatic turn (C-D-Eb-D) appears over sunny C major, alien.
//
//   A' Section (mm. 61-88): Tempo I, E minor
//      Return of the chase, intensified. Stretto passages — fragments piling
//      atop each other. The climax almost states Phrase A complete, but in
//      inversion. Then collapse.
//
// The tritone F#-C is the movement's destabilizing agent. In the hidden theme,
// F# appears as part of the stepwise ascent (E-F#-G) and C appears in the
// chromatic turn. Here, extracted and forced together, they create an interval
// that can resolve nowhere — or everywhere.
//
// ============================================================================

